  "summary": "Hester and Philip engage in a conversation where Hester expresses her feelings of inadequacy, her history of suicidal ideation since age fourteen, and her resentment toward her mother. She describes a failed attempt to live independently and a failed romantic pursuit of an older, married man who lied to her. Hester also reveals that discovering she was adopted at age sixteen contributed to her insecurity, and she expresses frustration that her mother was always right, which made Hester feel useless.\n\nThe conversation turns to the death of Hester's mother. Hester reveals that a man named Donald Craig believes she killed her mother and has offered to marry her if she confesses. Hester vehemently denies the killing, though she notes that others, including Mary and Coulston, also suspect her. Philip dismisses Donald Craig as a pompous fool and suggests that Hester should not marry him. As Philip kisses Hester to cheer her up, his wife, Mary Darland, enters the room. Mary ignores Philip's attempts to explain the kiss or reconcile, eventually leaving the room after delivering a tray of soup.\n\nIn a separate scene, a butler informs Calgary that a pretty young lady wishes to see him. Calgary is surprised but instructs the butler to bring her up. Upon her arrival, Calgary recognizes the visitor and welcomes her into his room.",
